## PRIOR FINDINGS (build on these; do NOT duplicate; you MUST surface >=1 that these missed)
- F-2-1 [benchmark/P0] The compiled-parity lane fits entirely in 2 non-frozen files (new compiled-parity.cjs sibling + orchestrator hook at run-skill-benchmark.cjs:219 and :308); the frozen trio stays byte-identical.
- F-2-2 [benchmark/P0] Vacuous-parity trap: SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING=1 alone is insufficient. resolve.cjs:41-42 requires the per-hub activation manifest to read servingAuthority==='compiled'; otherwise resolveRoute returns null and compiled-route.cjs:39 emits a legacy sentinel that a naive lane reads as 'compiled matches legacy'.
- F-2-3 [benchmark/P0] Shape impedance: the compiled engine emits targetQualifiedIds + decisionAction + observedIntents (verified in route-gold.typed.json), but the frozen evaluateRouteGold reads observed.observedResources as surface paths (score-skill-benchmark.cjs:903-904). Direct comparison is vocabulary-incompatible.
- F-2-4 [archiving/P1] Spec-tree resolver coupling: compiled-route.cjs:16-21 resolves the resolver from inside .opencode/specs/.../011-runtime-engine/lib/resolve.cjs. Specs are mutable planning artifacts; a rename silently breaks the resolver and the catch at compiled-route.cjs:36-39 returns the legacy sentinel, producing vacuous parity. ZERO activation/manifest.json or compiled/route-gold.typed.json live under .opencode/skills/<hub>/ — all 19 + 12 live under specs only.
- F-2-5 [benchmark/P2] Hub-type detection (isHubTypeSkill, run-skill-benchmark.cjs:68 keys on hub-router.json) is misaligned with compiled-serving eligibility (keys on activation manifest + advisor-recommend.ts COMPILED_ROUTING_HUBS allowlist). A hub can have --route-gold auto-on while compiled-parity is structurally N/A.
- F-1-1 [catalogs/P1] The sk-design hub catalog needs a dedicated compiled-routing entry because it already owns the hub's manager-shell routing inventory.
- F-1-2 [catalogs/P1] Compiled routing belongs inside the existing advisor_recommend feature because compiledRoute is an optional field on that tool's recommendation schema.
- F-1-3 [activation/P0] The feature-flag governance catalog must document compiled-routing polarity and rollback because the live handler directly gates enrichment on SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING.
- F-1-4 [catalogs/P1] Child-mode catalogs must not repeat compiled-router behavior because compiled routing resolves the hub mode before the selected packet is loaded.
- F-1-5 [sk-doc-templates/P0] Catalog text must change with the rollout phase because the authoring contract permits only shipped current reality, including explicitly labelled flag-gated compatibility behavior.
- F-1-6 [unnamed/P2] The twenty-fourth catalog tree uses uppercase FEATURE-CATALOG.md, so canonical lowercase-only discovery silently undercounts the catalog population.
- F-1-7 [unnamed/P0] The current compiled-router source anchor is unsuitable for a durable catalog because it imports its resolver from the mutable spec tree.
- F-3-1 [playbooks/P1] New-router cases belong in the seven compiled-eligible hub root playbooks plus system-skill-advisor, while child-mode playbooks remain out of scope.
- F-3-2 [playbooks/P0] The minimal canonical state corpus is four scenarios covering flag-off, flag-on fresh, drift-to-legacy, and causal seven-hub serving status.
- F-3-3 [unnamed/P0] The prompt-time hook cannot machine-enforce compiled routing because its recommendation type and rendered brief discard compiledRoute.
- F-3-4 [sk-code-align/P0] The public compiled front door supplies only prompt text, but sk-code surfaceBundle routing requires risk-slice and certificate context, so code-opencode cannot be proven end-to-end through the current interface.
- F-3-5 [playbooks/P1] The sk-doc root playbook still validates the retired flat RESOURCE_MAP router rather than the live eleven-packet hub contract.
- F-3-6 [activation/P0] The current legacy sentinel collapses flag-disabled, missing or malformed manifest, legacy authority, and engine failure, so a serving-status playbook cannot classify cause.
- F-3-7 [playbooks/P1] Prior LUNA route runs repeatedly exhausted the 150-second ceiling, so model timeout must be separated from routing correctness.
- F-3-8 [sk-code-align/P0] The named verify_alignment_drift.py gate checks language files but does not inspect the Markdown RESOURCE_MAP whose parent-child equality it is expected to enforce.
- F-4-1 [archiving/P0] The storage contract permits only a report JSON, its rendered Markdown, and an optional README, so compiled-vs-legacy parity must be embedded in the canonical Lane C report pair rather than archived as a copied spec-tree artifact.
- F-4-2 [archiving/P0] The existing baseline label is the frozen legacy pre-optimization anchor and must not be repurposed as the compiled-parity baseline.
- F-4-3 [activation/P0] The runtime resolves serving state from 010-live-activation while 006-parent-hub-rollout contains candidate manifests with different authority, so archiving the candidate tree can record non-serving evidence.
- F-4-4 [archiving/P1] Lane C live reports currently omit the exact model and variant even though the executor selects them, so a live-gpt-5-6-luna-high folder alone cannot prove the required LUNA HIGH subject.
- F-4-5 [unnamed/P1] Durable benchmark reports serialize an absolute worktree root, making archived evidence dependent on the originating machine and worktree path.
- F-5-1 [unnamed/P0] The advisor launcher strips SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING before spawning the daemon, so a parent-profile canary cannot activate the live advisor path.
- F-5-2 [activation/P0] Both current enablement predicates are fleet-global, so the specified hub-by-hub P4 cannot be performed by flipping those predicates literally.
- F-5-3 [activation/P0] All seven activation manifests are already compiled-serving, so making an unset flag mean enabled would activate the entire fleet simultaneously.
- F-5-4 [activation/P1] The existing routing drift workflow does not trigger on activation manifests, compiled runtime files, hub directives, or the advisor launcher.
- F-5-5 [unnamed/P0] HUB_CHILD is not merely a duplicated eligibility allowlist; it is also the runtime engine-location map, so removing it via manifest eligibility alone would break engine loading.
- F-5-6 [activation/P1] The ENV reference needs daemon-propagation and restart semantics in addition to flag polarity because advisor flags only work when forwarded to the resident child.
- F-5-7 [activation/P1] Each hub directive still encodes exact =1 opt-in semantics and therefore must change in the same commit as that hub enters the default-on cohort.
