    12	---
    13	
    14	# Feature Catalog Snippet Template
    15	
    16	Per-feature reference files for split feature catalogs. Use this template for the one-file-per-feature contract described in the main feature catalog template.
    17	
    18	---
    19	
    20	## 1. OVERVIEW
    21	
    22	Each feature file is the canonical home for detailed current-reality reference material. The root `feature-catalog.md` stays readable by summarizing the feature and linking here, while the per-feature file carries the fuller behavior description, structured source-file references, validation anchors, and concise metadata.
    23	
    24	| Use this template when | Do NOT use this template for |
    25	|---|---|
    26	| Creating one file per catalog feature | General reusable prose fragments |
    27	| Adding a feature to an existing split catalog | Replacing the root feature catalog |
    28	| A feature needs structured source-file + test references | Splitting one feature across multiple files without clear reason |
    29	| A feature maps to a named MCP tool or CLI command | Features not yet shipped (mark as not-yet-implemented in HOW IT WORKS instead) |
    30	
    31	---
    32	
    33	## 2. FRONTMATTER CONTRACT
    34	
    35	All per-feature snippet files require this frontmatter block. Fields marked `# required` must appear in every file; fields marked `# optional` may be omitted if not applicable.
    36	
    37	```yaml
    38	---
    39	title: "{FEATURE_NAME}"                           # required — human-readable label, matches H3 in root catalog
    40	description: "{ONE_LINE_FEATURE_SUMMARY}"         # required — shown in catalog tables and advisor doc matches
    41	trigger_phrases:                                   # required — drives skill-advisor routing (doc-trigger harvest; memory does not index skill docs)
    42	  - "{primary trigger phrase}"
    43	  - "{alternate phrasing}"
    44	  - "{tool or command name}"
    45	  - "{user-visible label if different}"
    46	importance_tier: "important"                       # optional — omit unless this is a Tier 1 critical feature
    47	version: 1.0.0.0
    48	---
    49	```
    50	
    51	**Field notes:**
    52	- `trigger_phrases` must match the H3 feature heading used in the root `feature-catalog.md` (plus natural language alternates)
    53	- `importance_tier: "important"` is reserved for features that should rank as high-signal in skill-advisor routing — omit for standard entries
    54	- `title` and `description` should mirror the root catalog entry for this feature (same wording, same scope)
    55	
    56	---
    57	
    58	## 3. TEMPLATE SCAFFOLD
    59	
    60	Copy everything inside the code fence into `feature-catalog/{CATEGORY_DIR}/{FEATURE_SLUG}.md`. Both placeholder values must be kebab-case:
    61	
    62	```markdown
    63	---
    64	title: "{FEATURE_NAME}"
    65	description: "{OVERVIEW_ONE_LINE}"
    66	trigger_phrases:
    67	  - "{primary trigger phrase}"
    68	  - "{alternate phrasing}"
    69	  - "{tool or command name}"
    70	  - "{user-visible label if different}"
    71	# importance_tier: "important"   # uncomment only for Tier 1 critical features
    72	version: 1.0.0.0
    73	---
    74	
    75	# {FEATURE_NAME} ({tool_name_or_command})
    76	
    77	<!-- sk-doc-template: skill_asset_feature_catalog -->
    78	
    79	## 1. OVERVIEW
    80	
    81	{OVERVIEW_ONE_LINE}
    82	
    83	{OVERVIEW_DETAIL}
    84	
    85	---
    86	
    87	## 2. HOW IT WORKS
    88	
    89	<!-- Short section (≤3 paragraphs): write plain prose and delete the sub-headings below.
    90	     Long section (>3 paragraphs): keep or rename sub-headings and delete this comment. -->
    91	
    92	### {PRIMARY_BEHAVIOR_ASPECT}
    93	
    94	{Description of the core behavior from the caller's perspective.}
    95	
    96	### {SECONDARY_BEHAVIOR_ASPECT}
    97	
    98	{Description of a distinct aspect — quality gates, routing logic, async behavior, etc.}
    99	
   100	<!-- Add further H3 sub-headings as needed. Common ones:
   101	     Configuration | Quality Gates | Edge Cases | Async & Safety | Post-Action Behavior -->
   102	
   103	---
   104	
   105	## 3. SOURCE FILES
   106	
   107	### Implementation
   108	
   109	| File | Layer | Role |
   110	|---|---|---|
   111	| `{IMPLEMENTATION_FILE_1}` | {Handler\|Shared\|Script} | {ROLE_1} |
   112	| `{IMPLEMENTATION_FILE_2}` | {Handler\|Shared\|Script} | {ROLE_2} |
   113	
   114	### Validation And Tests
   115	
   116	| File | Type | Role |
   117	|---|---|---|
   118	| `{TEST_FILE_1}` | {Automated test\|Manual playbook} | {TEST_ROLE_1} |
   119	| `{TEST_FILE_2}` | {Automated test\|Manual playbook} | {TEST_ROLE_2} |
   120	
   121	---
   122	
   123	## 4. SOURCE METADATA
   124	
   125	- Group: {CATEGORY_NAME}
   126	- Canonical catalog source: `feature-catalog.md`
   127	- Feature file path: `{CATEGORY_DIR}/{FEATURE_SLUG}.md`
   128	
   129	Related references:
   130	- [{neighboring-feature}.md]({neighboring-feature}.md) — {brief description}
   131	- [{neighboring-feature}.md]({neighboring-feature}.md) — {brief description}
   132	```
   133	
   134	---
   135	
   136	## 4. AUTHORING NOTES
   137	
   138	**Frontmatter**
   139	- `trigger_phrases` must align with the H3 feature heading in the root catalog — copy the heading exactly as one phrase, then add natural-language alternates and the tool/command name.
   140	- Use `importance_tier: "important"` only for features that must surface in every relevant search — omit for standard catalog entries.
   141	
   142	**H1 heading**
   143	- Include the tool or command name in parentheses when the feature maps to a named MCP tool, CLI command, or function: `# Memory indexing (memory_save)`.
   144	- Omit the parenthetical if the feature is a subsystem behavior with no single named entry point.
   145	
   146	**OVERVIEW**
   147	- First paragraph: one-liner summary matching the root catalog description.
   148	- Second paragraph: additional detail — typical caller, failure modes, or non-obvious scope. Do not repeat the root catalog verbatim.
   149	
   150	**HOW IT WORKS**
   151	- Describe behavior from the caller/operator perspective, not from the implementation.
   152	- If the section exceeds 3 paragraphs, break it into H3 sub-headings — e.g. `### Core Behavior`, `### Quality Gates`, `### Configuration`, `### Edge Cases`. Don't let a wall of prose stand without navigation anchors.
   153	- Use the optional subsections (Trigger / Auto-Fire Path / Class / Caveats) for features with distinct runtime modes (auto-fire, half-auto, manual); omit them for simple request/response features.
   154	- If the feature is not yet implemented, say so clearly in this section and leave SOURCE FILES tables empty or stub-only.
   155	
   156	**SOURCE FILES**
   157	- Layer column valid values: `Handler`, `Shared`, `Script`, `Test`.
   158	- Type column valid values: `Automated test`, `Manual playbook`.
   159	- List only stable public-facing paths. Omit transient build artifacts or generated files.
   160	- If no implementation files exist yet, add a single row: `| — | — | Not yet implemented |`.
   161	
   162	**SOURCE METADATA**
   163	- Preserve the feature file path after publication — other docs link to this path. Category folders and per-feature files use descriptive kebab-case names without numeric prefixes.
   164	- Related references: link to the immediately adjacent features in the same category directory so readers can navigate without returning to the root catalog.
   165	
   166	---
   167	
   168	## 5. CHECKLIST
   169	
   170	Before publishing a per-feature snippet file, verify:
   171	
   172	```markdown
   173	Structure:
   174	- [ ] Frontmatter has title, description, and trigger_phrases
   175	- [ ] importance_tier present only if this is a Tier 1 critical feature
   176	- [ ] Template marker present after H1: <!-- sk-doc-template: skill_asset_feature_catalog -->
   177	- [ ] All four body sections present: OVERVIEW, HOW IT WORKS, SOURCE FILES, SOURCE METADATA
   178	
   179	Content:
   180	- [ ] trigger_phrases include the H3 heading from root catalog plus natural-language alternates
   181	- [ ] H1 includes tool name in parens when feature maps to a named tool or command
   182	- [ ] HOW IT WORKS describes shipped behavior (not speculative roadmap)
   183	- [ ] Source-file tables reference real, existing paths
   184	- [ ] "Canonical catalog source" uses lowercase kebab-case: feature-catalog.md
   185	
   186	Quality:
   187	- [ ] This per-feature file is linked from the matching root catalog entry
   188	- [ ] Related references at the bottom point to real neighboring feature files
   189	```

