 succeeded in 0ms:
   205	---
   206	
   207	## 4. HOW IT WORKS: CREATION WORKFLOW
   208	
   209	Follow this workflow in order.
   210	
   211	1. Read the target system docs, source files, command surfaces, MCP tool lists, tests, and existing README material before drafting the catalog.
   212	2. Decide whether a catalog is warranted; use a README summary instead when the feature surface is small, complete, stable, or too volatile for a maintained catalog.
   213	3. Decide the category taxonomy before writing prose.
   214	4. Stabilize category names, feature names, and feature slugs before polishing descriptions.
   215	5. Create `feature-catalog/feature-catalog.md` from `assets/feature-catalog-template.md`.
   216	6. Create one category folder per root section using a descriptive kebab-case slug such as `category-name`; the root catalog listing defines display order.
   217	7. Create one per-feature file for each root entry using `assets/feature-catalog-snippet-template.md`.
   218	8. Write concise root summaries and link each feature to its per-feature file.
   219	9. Fill each per-feature `## 2. HOW IT WORKS` section with current behavior.
   220	10. Use plain prose for short `HOW IT WORKS` sections and H3 subheadings for sections longer than three paragraphs.
   221	11. Fill implementation source tables and validation or test anchor tables for every feature claim.
   222	12. Fill `## 4. SOURCE METADATA`, including group, canonical file path, and related references.
   223	13. Validate the root catalog and each per-feature leaf file with shared validation (see §7).
   224	14. Manually verify feature-file links, root-entry parity, source anchors, and current-state wording.
   225	
   226	Authoring order matters:
   227	
   228	- Stabilize names and slugs before polishing prose.
   229	- Finish root taxonomy before expanding file-level detail.
   230	- Use implementation and test anchors to justify every feature summary.
   231	
   232	---
   233	
   234	## 5. ROOT CATALOG REQUIREMENTS
   235	
   236	The root catalog is the top-level inventory and navigation layer.
   237	
   238	It owns:
   239	
   240	- Frontmatter with title, description, trigger phrases, last updated date, and four-part version.
   241	- A short H1 intro describing the current feature surface.
   242	- `## 1. OVERVIEW`.
   243	- Numbered H2 capability sections by category.
   244	- H3 feature entries with concise descriptions.
   245	- Current-reality summaries.
   246	- Explicit links to per-feature files.
   247	
   248	Root summaries should answer:
   249	
   250	- What this feature does.
   251	- What its current reality is.
   252	- Where to find source-file and test detail.
   253	
   254	Package highlights for root catalogs:
   255	
   256	- Use frontmatter, including `trigger_phrases`.
   257	- Include a short H1 intro.
   258	- Do not include a Table of Contents.
   259	- Do not use `<!-- ANCHOR -->` navigation comments.
   260	- Start numbered H2 sections with `## 1. OVERVIEW`.
   261	
   262	Do not overload the root catalog with:
   263	
   264	- Exhaustive source-file tables.
   265	- Full scenario matrices.
   266	- Speculative future-state design.
   267	- Long implementation explanations.
   268	- Roadmap detail.
   269	
   270	That information belongs in per-feature files, playbooks, or specs.
   271	
   272	---
   273	
   274	## 6. PER-FEATURE FILE REQUIREMENTS
   275	
   276	Each per-feature file is the detailed reference entry for one catalog item.
   277	
   278	Required structure:
   279	
   280	1. `## 1. OVERVIEW`
   281	2. `## 2. HOW IT WORKS`
   282	3. `## 3. SOURCE FILES`
   283	4. `## 4. SOURCE METADATA`
   284	
   285	Each per-feature file must include:
   286	
   287	- Frontmatter with stable `title`, one-line `description`, `trigger_phrases`, and a four-part `version`.
   288	- At least three trigger phrases matching the H3 heading in the root catalog.
   289	- An H1 matching the feature, with a tool or command name in parentheses when relevant.
   290	- A concise overview of the feature.
   291	- A behavior-focused `HOW IT WORKS` section.
   292	- Implementation source tables with `File | Layer | Role` columns.
   293	- Validation or test anchors with `File | Type | Role` columns.
   294	- Metadata including group, canonical file path, and related references.
   295	
   296	`HOW IT WORKS` subheading rule:
   297	
   298	- Use plain prose when the section is three paragraphs or fewer.
   299	- Add H3 subheadings when the section exceeds three paragraphs.
   300	- Preferred H3 examples include `### Core Behavior`, `### Quality Gates`, `### Configuration`, `### Edge Cases`, and `### Async & Safety`.
   301	- Describe behavior from the caller or operator perspective, not the implementation perspective.
   302	
   303	Content rule:
   304	
   305	- Describe behavior that exists now.
   306	- If a rollout or compatibility layer is documented, label it explicitly.
   307	- Avoid roadmap or speculative wording unless the feature itself is a documented compatibility or feature-flag surface.
   308	
   309	---
   310	
   311	## 7. PLAYBOOK AND VALIDATION BOUNDARY
   312	
   313	Feature catalogs and manual testing playbooks serve different purposes.
   314	
   315	| Document | Primary Question |
   316	|---|---|
   317	| Feature catalog | What does the system do today? |
   318	| Manual testing playbook | How do we validate that behavior manually? |
   319	
   320	Cross-reference rule:
   321	
   322	- Playbooks should link back to the matching catalog entry when one exists.
   323	- Catalogs should stay focused on current behavior, not test execution detail.
   324	- Manual execution scenario matrices belong in playbooks, not catalogs.
   325	
   326	Validation workflow — run from the repo root so the validator resolves the `feature_catalog` doc type on per-feature leaves (leaf detection accepts the canonical `feature-catalog/<category>/` path during the bounded compatibility window):
   327	
   328	```bash
   329	# New-content naming guard. The staging root must contain only the newly authored
   330	# canonical feature-catalog package, never an ancestor with shipped legacy roots.
   331	python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/shared/scripts/check_no_hyphenated_catalog_content.py <new-content-staging-root>
   332	
   333	# Root catalog (detected as the readme doc type)
   334	python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/shared/scripts/validate_document.py <target-skill>/feature-catalog/feature-catalog.md
   335	python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/shared/scripts/extract_structure.py <target-skill>/feature-catalog/feature-catalog.md
   336	
   337	# Each per-feature leaf (detected as the feature_catalog doc type; validates the Validation And Tests table taxonomy)
   338	python3 .opencode/skills/sk-doc/shared/scripts/validate_document.py <target-skill>/feature-catalog/<category-name>/feature-name.md
   339	```
   340	
   341	The staging scope is mandatory until shipped underscore roots are migrated. Do not run this guard against `.opencode/skills` or another ancestor containing legacy `feature_catalog/` or `manual_testing_playbook/` trees.
   342	
   343	The validator machine-checks the root-catalog structure and each leaf's Validation And Tests table, but not cross-file link targets or source-anchor accuracy. Manually verify:
   344	
   345	- Every root entry links to an existing per-feature file.
   346	- Every per-feature file is represented in the root catalog.
   347	- Source-file tables reference real, stable paths.
   348	- Validation or test tables reference real, stable paths.
   349	- Catalog claims describe shipped behavior, not speculative roadmap.
   350	- Cross-file links resolve.
   351	- Runtime docs avoid mutable spec or phase packet history.
   352	
   353	Validator boundary:
   354	
   355	- `validate_document.py` checks root-catalog structure and, for per-feature leaves reached by a repo-root path, the Validation And Tests table taxonomy.
   356	- Cross-file link resolution is enforced in CI by `check-markdown-links.cjs`.
   357	- Per-feature link correctness and source-anchor accuracy still require manual review.
   358	
   359	---
   360	
   361	## 8. RULES
   362	
   363	### ✅ ALWAYS
   364	
   365	1. Use `assets/feature-catalog-template.md` for the root catalog scaffold.
   366	2. Use `assets/feature-catalog-snippet-template.md` for per-feature files.
   367	3. Preserve the canonical root path `feature-catalog/feature-catalog.md`.
   368	4. Name category folders with a descriptive kebab-case slug such as `category-name`; let the root catalog index own display order.
   369	5. Keep per-feature filenames stable after publication.
   370	6. Keep per-feature filenames free of numeric prefixes.
   371	7. Include source-file and validation anchors for every feature claim.
   372	8. Describe current shipped behavior from the caller or operator perspective.
   373	9. Keep the root catalog inventory-first and navigation-focused.
   374	10. Put implementation truth in per-feature files.
   375	11. Run shared validation on the root catalog and per-feature leaves before delivery.
   376	12. Manually verify cross-file links, source anchors, and root-entry to feature-file parity.
   377	13. Consume global standards and validators from `../shared/` instead of duplicating them here.
   378	
   379	### ⛔ NEVER
   380	

